comments: the old lighting is what makes unsettling

This trailer is scary because of the sudden burst of energy automotive energy.
Normally you'd have to turn the key, Wait for the starter to ignite the engine, Wait a moment for the engine to warm up and check your surroundings, Turn on the lights, Change gears to Drive and move forward. All of this taking about 10 seconds or so. But here! Christine just turns her lights on and races after you just one second after being motionless. Just like an animal predator making it's move to take your life.
Overall: The logic behind this commercial's simplicity is what make's it an actual good jump scare.

comments:
If you haven't watched " Flight " then your missing out on a near perfect film & that's extremely rare in Hollywood these day's or in Hollywood period...

You usually have to watch a movie that was funded individually which is basically a low budget indy film but that doesn't detract from the fact that most of those movies take more risks/are more gritty/believable & as enjoyable as they are but there not box office draws... As it's about butts on seats & Hollywood doesn't like taking chances if it can help it but with " Flight " it takes that chance & the overall movie is well worth seeing to the end...

There are a lot of things going on within this movie (which I won't mention as I wouldn't want to spoil) as you have character studies/someone trying to justify to himself that what he did, even though, sheer unfathomable & almost unbelievably, it's one movie that'll keep you sitting all the way through to the end to see where these character's end up...

And again I have to commend Hollywood as most of their movies won't & very rarely risk such a ballsy & gusty story & its finale...

10 Out Of 10 from me, but you go & watch it & make up your own mind!..

comments:
It's important to point out that practically everything shown in the trailer is make believe (after the start of the "experiment"). No one was struck by a baton in the real experiment. Additionally, in the real experiment, the guards were actually encouraged to psychologically mistreat the prisoners - so that's exactly what happened. Emotional violence, NOT physical. Of course, that doesn't make for a good movie.

The SPE didn't demonstrate what the "environment" does to people, it demonstrated how pliable people are. But Milgram already demonstrated that; much more clearly, conclusively, and terrifyingly (imo).

0:14: Worse. UN-dead.

Turns 10 today!
Even being dead we need some warmth from each other
Had no idea this was based on Issac Marion's young-adult novel
A new spin of 'Romeo & Juliet' by director Jonathan Levine unexpectedly as a revitalized, optimistic take on the play
Palmer and Hoult are the central core of the story beginning an unexpected romance between the living and the dead
'R' in particular is adorable to watch only able to communicate through limited speech and we hear more of his internal dialogue
The premise is a smidge corny and some stuff plot wise is skimpy but there's a likability to these two saving mankind in the most unexpected way
It also still gives horror lovers some pulse-quickening spooks and paranormal comedy enthusiasts plenty to cackle about
A big departure from the typical zombie fare we are used to but it remains subversive rewriting the genre itself giving a self-aware edge making lots of inverses
Few stories like this exist on a particular romance of this kind yet it's refreshing to see from the undead POV
The author Marion got himself out of a deep depression thanks to the source material feeling much like 'R' being isolated
The movie also asks what makes being human a human being while also delivering a great message of offering hope among the bleakest of circumstances
People want to try to be better and we have to learn to suck it up, it's hard to accept change, is not feeling anything better to avoid feeling altogether?, maybe learning to live and reconnect is the cure
If you think about it there's even a real world parallel of a wall built to keep the bad people out and the normal ones safe
For all the Twilight haters rest assured the romance isn't shoved in your face like a lot of YA adaptations
'Warm Bodies' tells us how to be human again through commentary on consumerism, narcissism, and xenophobia
